<dl id="n25068e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25068e">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25068e"> 68(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> beingstalks / sitting on their arts / was / were = dwell</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Even the substantive verb &lsquo;<mark>to be</mark>,&rsquo; the &lsquo;most bodiless and colourless of all our words,&rsquo; is made up of the relics of several verbs which once had a distinct physical significance. &lsquo;Be&rsquo; contained the idea of &lsquo;growing&rsquo;; <mark>&lsquo;am, art, is,&rsquo; and &lsquo;are,&rsquo; the idea of &lsquo;sitting&rsquo;</mark>; <mark>&lsquo;was&rsquo; and &lsquo;were,&rsquo; that of &lsquo;dwelling&rsquo;</mark> or &lsquo; abiding.&rsquo; <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECTTT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ECTTT"><cite title="source">Tom Tit Tot</cite></a> (1898) 56</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14040b" href="c14all.htm#c14040b">VI.C.14:040(b)</a>, <a name="c14040c" href="c14all.htm#c14040c">VI.C.14:040(c)</a>, <a name="c14040d" href="c14all.htm#c14040d">VI.C.14:040(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
